          <h3 class="header-medium">Show Data Reliability</h3>
          <div class="grid-x">
            <div class="cell medium-3 large-2 feature-image-cell">
              {{!-- TODO: Edit this placeholder image! --}}
              <img src="http://via.placeholder.com/400x400" class="feature-image">
            </div>
            <div class="cell medium-9 large-10">
              <p>The Show Data Reliability feature expands the output shown on the four ACS profiles to reveal reliability measures associated with estimates – reliability measures include margins of error (MOEs) and Coefficients of Variation (CVs). Because data from the American Community Survey are derived from a survey, and are subject to sampling variability, measures of reliability help users gauge the consistency of the ACS and, ultimately, the degree to which they can trust any given statistic.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <h3 class="header-medium">Grayed Values</h3>
          <div class="grid-x">
            <div class="cell medium-3 large-2 feature-image-cell">
              {{!-- TODO: Edit this placeholder image! --}}
              <img src="http://via.placeholder.com/400x400" class="feature-image">
            </div>
            <div class="cell medium-9 large-10">
              <p>All four ACS profiles may include grayed values. When a value is grayed, it means that it is not statistically reliable enough for most applications. For estimates and MOEs with a CV, graying is an indication that the CV is greater than or equal to 20%. Data associated with count estimates of zero and top- and bottom-coded median estimates are also grayed to alert users that data are either unreliable, or of indeterminate reliability. Estimates and MOEs of differences between two areas and change over time for a selected area may also be grayed. Such graying indicates that the estimates are not statistically significant at a 90% confidence level.</p>
            </div>
          </div> 

